{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"14c1d728-9c4c-44e1-9e63-9fd45febee09","content":"Use `Assert.ThrowsException<T>` (MSTest) or `Assert.Throws<T>` (xUnit/NUnit) instead:\n\n```csharp\n[TestMethod]\npublic void CreateUser_NullEmail_ThrowsException()\n{\n    var service = new UserService();\n\n    var ex = Assert.ThrowsException<ArgumentNullException>(\n        () => service.CreateUser(null, \"John\"));\n\n    Assert.AreEqual(\"email\", ex.ParamName); // optional: verify details\n}\n```\n\n**Why switch:**\n- `[ExpectedException]` passes if *any* line throws, masking bugs (e.g., the constructor could throw instead of `CreateUser`)\n- `Assert.ThrowsException` scopes the assertion to the exact call\n- You can inspect the exception object (message, inner exception, etc.)","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"69b556b7-82f5-4e63-a6ec-c7d8dcae8e87","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about modernizing a C# test that uses the `[ExpectedException]` attribute. This is a general knowledge question — no need to explore any codebase.","outputTokens":259,"requestId":"A03C:243205:18BAD37:1C17D9E:69FE8DE0"},"id":"98ae43cf-1f5f-4d5e-8e8c-bd0f2bf542ba","timestamp":"2026-05-09T01:29:13.307Z","parentId":"9de89475-d364-44db-acc2-d25c50704709"}
